What are the types of the Legendary Pokemon?¶

In [49]:
legendary = df[(df['LEGENDARY'] == True)]

legendary2 = legendary[(legendary['TYPE 2'] != legendary['TYPE 1'])]
legendary2 = legendary['TYPE 2'].value_counts().reset_index()
legendary1 = legendary['TYPE 1'].value_counts().reset_index()
legendary = pd.merge(legendary1, legendary2, on="index", how="outer")
legendary = legendary.fillna(0)

legendary['TYPE Count'] = legendary['TYPE 1'] + legendary['TYPE 2']
legendary = legendary.sort_values('TYPE Count',ascending=False)

plt.barh(legendary['index'], legendary['TYPE Count'], color = 'silver')
plt.xlabel('Count')
plt.ylabel('Types of Pokemon')
plt.title('Types of the Legendary Pokemon')
Out[49]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Types of the Legendary Pokemon')

Most legendary Pokemon are overwhelmingly of type 'Psychic', but what Types are not cut to be legendary?

What is the distrubution of 'Attack'?¶

In [54]:
bins=range(0,200,20) #they act as containers
plt.hist(df["ATTACK"],bins,histtype="bar",rwidth=1.2,color='lightblue') #hist() is used to plot a histogram
plt.xlabel('Attack') #set the xlabel name
plt.ylabel('Count') #set the ylabel name
plt.plot()
plt.axvline(df['ATTACK'].mean(),linestyle='dashed',color='red') #draw a vertical line showing the average Attack value
plt.show()

We see the distribution is skewed slightly right, with a average around 76-77

What is the the relationship between Attack and Defense between Fire, Water, and Grass types?¶

In [129]:
fire=df[(df['TYPE 1']=='Fire') | ((df['TYPE 2'])=="Fire")] #fire contains all fire pokemons
water=df[(df['TYPE 1']=='Water') | ((df['TYPE 2'])=="Water")]  #all water pokemons
grass = df[(df['TYPE 1']=='Grass') | ((df['TYPE 2'])=="Grass")]  #all grass pokemons
plt.scatter(fire.ATTACK.head(50),fire.DEFENSE.head(50),color='Red',label='Fire',marker="*",s=50) #scatter plot
plt.scatter(water.ATTACK.head(50),water.DEFENSE.head(50),color='Blue',label="Water",s=25)
plt.scatter(grass.ATTACK.head(50),grass.DEFENSE.head(50),color='Green',label="Grass",marker=",",s=25)

plt.xlabel("Attack")
plt.ylabel("DEFENCE")
plt.legend()
plt.plot()
fig=plt.gcf()  #get the current figure using .gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(12,6) #set the size for the figure
plt.show()

Where do legendary Pokemon rank by total skill within their Type?¶

In [144]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
top_types=df['TYPE 1'].value_counts()[:18] #take the top 10 Types
df1=df[df['TYPE 1'].isin(top_types.index)] #take the pokemons of the type with highest numbers, top 10
sns.stripplot(x='TYPE 1',y='TOTAL',data=df1,hue='LEGENDARY') # this plot shows the points belonging to individual pokemons
# It is distributed by Type
plt.axhline(df1['TOTAL'].mean(),color='red',linestyle='dashed')
plt.show()

Legendary pokemon often rank higher than all Pokemon by skill.

What are the trends of type by Generation?¶

In [53]:
a=df.groupby(['GENERATION','TYPE 1']).count().reset_index()
a=a[['GENERATION','TYPE 1','TOTAL']]
a=a.pivot('GENERATION','TYPE 1','TOTAL')
a[['Water','Fire','Grass','Dragon','Normal','Rock','Flying','Electric']].plot(color=['b','r','g','#FFA500','brown','#6666ff','#001012','y'],marker='o')
fig=plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(12,6)
plt.show()

Water and Normal types tend to be the most popular Pokemon type for all 6 generations
